`ctx-cage` binary entry point: parses argv into `Cli`, resolves it into a `lifecycle::Resolved`, and drives the cage lifecycle to completion, mapping the child's exit code back to the process exit code.

Billed modes require `--allow-spend` or `CTX_CAGE_ALLOW_SPEND=1`; the always-available mode is `--self-test stub` (no-spend containment probe). `resolve_mode` (from `cli.rs`) does the actual gating — this file just ORs the flag and env var together via `env_allow_spend()` before passing to it.

`--contract` is special-cased outside clap parsing (`wants_contract()` scans raw argv for it) because it must win over the required `<target>` positional; when present, prints `cli::CONTRACT` and exits 0 without touching the rest of the pipeline.

`resolve_bin_paths() -> Result<BinPaths, CageError>` locates sibling binaries (`ctx-verify`, `ctx-context`, `ctx-scan`) relative to `current_exe()`'s directory, overridable via `CTX_VERIFY_BIN`/`CTX_CONTEXT_BIN`/`CTX_SCAN_BIN` env vars — used to bind them into the cage at `/cage/bin`. Fails with `CageError::Protocol` if `current_exe()` has no parent dir.

`build_resolved(cli, mode) -> Result<Resolved, CageError>` assembles the full lifecycle input; note `ctx-cage` never carries an API key itself, so any billed mode must be refused further downstream (in `lifecycle::execute` or `cli::resolve_mode`), not here.

Exit code handling: `run()`'s inner `i32` is truncated to `u8` via `unwrap_or(1)` — any code outside 0-255 collapses to 1. Host-level errors (`HostError::Cage`/`HostError::Resolve`) print to stderr and force exit code 1, distinct from the cage's own propagated exit code.

`emit()` mirrors an in-tree convention suppressing write failures on stdout/stderr, used to satisfy repo-wide lint restrictions on direct `print!`/`eprintln!` macros.